<br>
What you'll need for today's lesson: A pencil, pen, and several copies of this image <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/rawprint.jpg">www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/rawprint.jpg</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> print several incase you make a mistake. Please follow along with the tutorial.<br>
<br>
Raw Line art:<br>
<br>
Raw line art is line art without any lineweights and rendering. Line art looks bad that way. The only thing that can save it is either heavy coloring or rendering.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/rawlines.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/rawlines.gif">www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/rawlines.gif</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
This is one nasty looking image. Poorly drawn and no line variation or rendering. Never post something like this as finished line art unless you are planning to do some really good coloring. Our job today is to save it with without resorting to color.<br>
<br>
Line Weight:<br>
<br>
Line weights are the thickness of lines on an image. Varying the lineweights helps make an image more interesting. But you just can't randomly do it, there's a few rules to keep in mind if you want to have an effective use of line weight. Lineweights didn't click with me until after I learned to render, so if lineweight still puzzels you after this segment, don't fret.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/tutweightline.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/tutweightline.gif">www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/tutweightline.gif</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Rendering:<br>
<br>
Rendering is simply giving an image values and texture. This tutorial focuses on rendering with blacks and whites, as with inked line art. I've listed several basic ways to render in the image below.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/renderball.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/renderball.gif">www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/renderball.gif</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
There are all sorts of ways to render than I just shown in the image above. Study the way other comic book artist do it and also try different ways to get grey with a pen.<br>
<br>
Spotting blacks:<br>
<br>
You remeber that nasty image I drew, now it's time to figure out where to place the shadows. You can spot blacks in all sorts of ways, sketching on the image, sketching on a little image to the side, etc.. .The way I did it is similiar to putting a peice of paper on top the line art and marking where the shadows would be. Don't get too worried about making the shadows extremely accurate, just try to get it to make the image easy to read. Besides, many people don't notice mistakes made with shadows, or don't care.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/spotblacks.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/spotblacks.gif">www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/spotblacks.gif</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Putting it all together:<br>
<br>
Now it's time to put render the image. Put the peice of paper you spotted the blacks on behind the line art you want to render and trace the shadows onto it. I usually feather on softer material so I mostly stuck with hard blacks on the metal parts and light lines on the cape. I added some more blacks to the plants and cross-hatched the sky. I also added some lines to the ground to make it more interesting.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/tutfinal.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/tutfinal.gif">www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/tut/tutfinal.gif</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Still a bad image, but rendering has made it look a heck of a lot better. That's one of the powers of rendering, it looks good.<br>
<br>
If you followed along please share your results. I hope my lesson has made rendering a bit easier to understand.<br>
<br>
